"Roeckner E., Giorgetta M.A., Crueger T., Esch M., Pongratz J.","Historical and future anthropogenic emission pathways derived from coupled climate-carbon cycle simulations",2011,"Climatic Change","105","1",,"91","108",,,10.1007/s10584-010-9886-6,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79951809095&partnerID=40&md5=68ce8edfc3d136402bbfe84c4abff267","Max Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstraße 53, 20146 Hamburg, Germany; Department of Global Ecology, Carnegie Institution of Washington, 260 Panama St., Stanford, CA 94305, United States","Roeckner, E., Max Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstraße 53, 20146 Hamburg, Germany; Giorgetta, M.A., Max Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstraße 53, 20146 Hamburg, Germany; Crueger, T., Max Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstraße 53, 20146 Hamburg, Germany; Esch, M., Max Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstraße 53, 20146 Hamburg, Germany; Pongratz, J., Max Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstraße 53, 20146 Hamburg, Germany, Department of Global Ecology, Carnegie Institution of Washington, 260 Panama St., Stanford, CA 94305, United States","Using a coupled climate-carbon cycle model, fossil fuel carbon dioxide (CO 2) emissions are derived through a reverse approach of prescribing atmospheric CO 2 concentrations according to observations and future projections, respectively. In the second half of the twentieth century, the implied fossil fuel emissions, and also the carbon uptake by land and ocean, are within the range of observational estimates. Larger discrepancies exist in the earlier period (1860-1960), with small fossil fuel emissions and uncertain emissions from anthropogenic land cover change. In the IPCC SRES A1B scenario, the simulated fossil fuel emissions more than double until 2050 (17 GtC/year) and then decrease to 12 GtC/year by 2100. In addition to A1B, an aggressive mitigation scenario was employed, developed within the European ENSEMBLES project, that peaks at 530 ppm CO 2(equiv) around 2050 and then decreases to approach 450 ppm during the twenty-second century. Consistent with the prescribed pathway of atmospheric CO 2 in E1, the implied fossil fuel emissions increase from currently 8 GtC/year to about 10 by 2015 and decrease thereafter. In the 2050s (2090s) the emissions decrease to 3.4 (0.5) GtC/year, respectively. As in previous studies, our model simulates a positive climate-carbon cycle feedback which tends to reduce the implied emissions by roughly 1 GtC/year per degree global warming. Further, our results suggest that the 450 ppm stabilization scenario may not be sufficient to fulfill the European Union climate policy goal of limiting the global temperature increase to a maximum of 2°C compared to pre-industrial levels. © 2010 Springer Science+Business Media B.V.",,"Anthropogenic emissions; Atmospheric CO; Carbon cycle models; Carbon cycles; Carbon uptake; Climate policy; European Union; Fossil fuel emissions; Future projections; Global temperatures; Land-cover change; Pre-industrial levels; Twentieth century; Atmospheric aerosols; Carbon dioxide; Fossil fuels; Global warming; Climate models; anthropogenic source; carbon cycle; carbon emission; concentration (composition); emission control; environmental policy; estimation method; European Union; fossil fuel; global warming; land cover; numerical model; observational method; stabilization; temperature profile; twentieth century",,,,,,"Allen, M., Ingram, W., Constraints on future changes in climate and the hydrological cycle (2002) Nature, 419, pp. 224-232; Boucher, O., Pham, M., History of sulfate aerosol radiative forcings (2002) Geophys Res Lett, 29, p. 1308. , doi:10.1029/2001GL014048; Brasseur, G.P., Roeckner, E., Impact of improved air quality on the future evolution of climate (2005) Geophys Res Lett, 32, p. 23704. , doi:10.1029/2005GL023902; Brohan, P., Kennedy, J.J., Harris, I., Tett, S.F.B., Jones, P.D., Uncertainty estimates in regional and global observed tem